******
[5] Guinea
Date: Mon 4 Mar 2019
Source: African Daily Voice [abridged, edited]
https://protect2.fireeye.com/url?k=cadf6256-96fb9437-cadd9b63-0cc47a6d17e0-98dcc77eb18fc208&u=https://africandailyvoice.com/en/2019/03/04/guinea-outbreak-of-the-measles-epidemic-reported-in-10-districts-of-the-country/


Measles vaccination in Guinea was drastically reduced during the 2014-2015 Ebola epidemic, partly because attention and most resources were focused on Ebola management but mainly due to fear.

A new outbreak of the measles epidemic has just been reported in a dozen districts of the country, according to official sources. More than 200 suspected children with measles have been identified and 88 of them are already affected by the disease, Dr. Sakoba Keita, Director General of the National Agency of Health Security (ANSS) said on [Sat 2 Mar 2019] on national radio.

According to him, children already suffering from measles are hospitalized in the centers of responses and treatment of diseases with epidemic potential, implanted already all around the country, following the appearance of the Ebola fever in Guinea between 2014 and 2015.

With the support of foreign partners, the National Health Security Agency supplies health facilities for the treatment of potential epidemic diseases in the country with the necessary products and medicines to cope with urgent cases.

This measles outbreak is explained by the low immunization coverage rate of children under 5 years of age who are identified in high-risk epidemic areas. Nowadays, according to statistics from the Ministry of Health, only 25% of middle-aged children have correctly received all vaccine doses throughout the country.

"We are planning to send teams to the most remote locations so that every child can be properly vaccinated in time," said Dr. Keita.

